<subSubSection id="908B6500CE2A550590A12B3FFE77FD1A" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="575" pageId="1" pageNumber="573" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="D82E368BCE2A550790A12B3FFCA8F891" blockId="1.[151,1436,1852,1987]" pageId="1" pageNumber="573">
<emphasis id="EAE5EA99CE2A550790A12B3FFEB5F8BD" bold="true" box="[151,256,1852,1878]" pageId="1" pageNumber="573">Remark.</emphasis>
As noted above, the original description of this species was rather superficial and incomplete, especially as regards the crucial gonopodal structure (
<bibRefCitation id="BC004B7ACE2A5507924F2B63FCA5F891" author="Pocock, R. I." box="[633,784,1888,1914]" pageId="1" pageNumber="573" pagination="131 - 174" refId="ref3370" refString="Pocock, R. I. (1892) Report upon two collections of Myriapoda sent from Ceylon by Mr. E. E. Green, and from various parts of southern India by Mr. Edgar Thurston, of the Government Central Museum, Madras. Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society, 7, 131 - 174. [https: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / item / 95456  page / 7 / mode / 1 up]" type="journal article" year="1892">Pocock 1892</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D82E368BCE2A550790F12B87FBB2F828" blockId="1.[151,1436,1852,1987]" pageId="1" pageNumber="573">
<emphasis id="EAE5EA99CE2A550790F12B87FE05F875" bold="true" box="[199,432,1924,1950]" pageId="1" pageNumber="573">Brief redescription.</emphasis>
Body with 20 rings (19+T), length 
<emphasis id="EAE5EA99CE2A550793742B86FCE9F875" box="[834,860,1925,1950]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="573">ca</emphasis>
<quantity id="1F699B6ECE2A550793552B87FC7FF874" box="[867,970,1924,1951]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.05" pageId="1" pageNumber="573" unit="mm" value="10.5">10.5 mm</quantity>
. Coloration mostly dark grey-brown with contrasting pallid legs, tegument heavily coated with an earth crust (
<figureCitation id="40AA2A0ECE2A550793A22BABFC4FF828" box="[916,1018,1960,1987]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1857,1881]" captionTargetBox="[186,1401,181,1831]" captionTargetId="figure-15@2.[186,1401,181,1834]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Pyrgodesmus obscurus Pocock, 1892, male syntypes. 1. Original labels. 2. Both syntypes pierced with glass minutiae, shown relative to the length of an insect pin. 3. Habitus of a syntype, lateral view (after Pocock (1892)). 4. Picture of the same, lateral view. 5. Body rings 5–7 and gonopods in situ, ventral view. 6. Body rings 6–9 and gonopods in situ, ventrolateral view. 7 &amp; 8. Enlarged gonopods in situ, ventral and ventrolateral views, respectively. Figs 1–3, 7 and 8 not to scale. Images courtesy Dmitry Telnov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5709646" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5709646/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="573">Figs 4–6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D82E368BCE28550590F12C94FE79FDF2" blockId="3.[151,1437,150,789]" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">
Head fully covered from above by a flabellate anterior brim of a dome-shaped collum, the latter with 5+5 equal, distinct, rounded lobulations at anterior margin. Antennae C-shaped, short and clavate, antennomere 5 being the largest and subequal in length to 2 
<superScript id="2FE49BC3CE28550592162CDDFD85FF07" attach="none" box="[544,560,222,236]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">nd</superScript>
. Paramedian tubercles/crests (
<emphasis id="EAE5EA99CE28550593BD2CDCFC02FF12" bold="true" box="[907,951,223,249]" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">PM</emphasis>
) especially strongly developed, high, each tightly fused medially almost all along and only apically slightly divided, inclined anteriad on collum and rings 2–4, subvertical until ring 16, thereafter declined increasingly caudad (
<figureCitation id="40AA2A0ECE28550593B72D24FBB5FEAA" box="[897,1024,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1857,1881]" captionTargetBox="[186,1401,181,1831]" captionTargetId="figure-15@2.[186,1401,181,1834]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Pyrgodesmus obscurus Pocock, 1892, male syntypes. 1. Original labels. 2. Both syntypes pierced with glass minutiae, shown relative to the length of an insect pin. 3. Habitus of a syntype, lateral view (after Pocock (1892)). 4. Picture of the same, lateral view. 5. Body rings 5–7 and gonopods in situ, ventral view. 6. Body rings 6–9 and gonopods in situ, ventrolateral view. 7 &amp; 8. Enlarged gonopods in situ, ventral and ventrolateral views, respectively. Figs 1–3, 7 and 8 not to scale. Images courtesy Dmitry Telnov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5709646" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5709646/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">Figs 3 &amp; 4</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="EAE5EA99CE28550594202D24FBF7FEAA" bold="true" box="[1046,1090,295,321]" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">PM</emphasis>
mostly thickened and vaguely bilobate apically, only last few 
<emphasis id="EAE5EA99CE28550591C82D48FD9FFE8E" bold="true" box="[510,554,331,357]" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">PM</emphasis>
trilobate (
<figureCitation id="40AA2A0ECE28550592972D48FD5DFE8E" box="[673,744,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1857,1881]" captionTargetBox="[186,1401,181,1831]" captionTargetId="figure-15@2.[186,1401,181,1834]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Pyrgodesmus obscurus Pocock, 1892, male syntypes. 1. Original labels. 2. Both syntypes pierced with glass minutiae, shown relative to the length of an insect pin. 3. Habitus of a syntype, lateral view (after Pocock (1892)). 4. Picture of the same, lateral view. 5. Body rings 5–7 and gonopods in situ, ventral view. 6. Body rings 6–9 and gonopods in situ, ventrolateral view. 7 &amp; 8. Enlarged gonopods in situ, ventral and ventrolateral views, respectively. Figs 1–3, 7 and 8 not to scale. Images courtesy Dmitry Telnov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5709646" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5709646/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Paraterga very low, oblique and strongly declined, vaguely bi- or trilobate at lateral margin (
<figureCitation id="40AA2A0ECE28550592272D6CFDCCFE61" box="[529,633,367,394]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1857,1881]" captionTargetBox="[186,1401,181,1831]" captionTargetId="figure-15@2.[186,1401,181,1834]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Pyrgodesmus obscurus Pocock, 1892, male syntypes. 1. Original labels. 2. Both syntypes pierced with glass minutiae, shown relative to the length of an insect pin. 3. Habitus of a syntype, lateral view (after Pocock (1892)). 4. Picture of the same, lateral view. 5. Body rings 5–7 and gonopods in situ, ventral view. 6. Body rings 6–9 and gonopods in situ, ventrolateral view. 7 &amp; 8. Enlarged gonopods in situ, ventral and ventrolateral views, respectively. Figs 1–3, 7 and 8 not to scale. Images courtesy Dmitry Telnov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5709646" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5709646/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">Figs 3–6</figureCitation>
). Pore formula normal (5, 7, 9, 10, 12, 13, 15–19), ozopores borne on distinct porosteles on rings 5, 7, 9, 10, 12, 13 and 15, but opening flush on dorsal surface at base of caudal lobulation on rings 16–19 (
<figureCitation id="40AA2A0ECE28550591792DB4FE03FE39" box="[335,438,439,466]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1857,1881]" captionTargetBox="[186,1401,181,1831]" captionTargetId="figure-15@2.[186,1401,181,1834]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Pyrgodesmus obscurus Pocock, 1892, male syntypes. 1. Original labels. 2. Both syntypes pierced with glass minutiae, shown relative to the length of an insect pin. 3. Habitus of a syntype, lateral view (after Pocock (1892)). 4. Picture of the same, lateral view. 5. Body rings 5–7 and gonopods in situ, ventral view. 6. Body rings 6–9 and gonopods in situ, ventrolateral view. 7 &amp; 8. Enlarged gonopods in situ, ventral and ventrolateral views, respectively. Figs 1–3, 7 and 8 not to scale. Images courtesy Dmitry Telnov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5709646" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5709646/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">Figs 3–6</figureCitation>
). Surface below 
<emphasis id="EAE5EA99CE28550592442DB4FD2BFE3A" bold="true" box="[626,670,439,465]" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">PM</emphasis>
microgranulate, with neither 
<emphasis id="EAE5EA99CE28550593DD2DB4FBA7FE3A" bold="true" box="[1003,1042,439,465]" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">DL</emphasis>
nor 
<emphasis id="EAE5EA99CE28550594732DB5FBF8FE3B" bold="true" box="[1093,1101,438,464]" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">i</emphasis>
, nor 
<emphasis id="EAE5EA99CE28550594BE2DB5FB01FE3B" bold="true" box="[1160,1204,438,464]" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">Am</emphasis>
, nor 
<emphasis id="EAE5EA99CE28550594D92DB5FAAEFE3B" bold="true" box="[1263,1307,438,464]" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">Cm</emphasis>
discernible beneath an earth crust. 
<emphasis id="EAE5EA99CE28550591AF2DD8FE70FE1E" bold="true" box="[409,453,475,501]" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">PM</emphasis>
19 subhorizontal, fused medially and forming a deep caudal notch, tip of epiproct being slightly visible from above.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D82E368BCE28550590F12E20FE77FD1A" blockId="3.[151,1437,150,789]" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">
Legs robust, densely setose, each prefemur with a particularly long distoventral seta; claw small and simple (
<figureCitation id="40AA2A0ECE28550590A92E44FEA9FD89" box="[159,284,582,610]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1857,1881]" captionTargetBox="[186,1401,181,1831]" captionTargetId="figure-15@2.[186,1401,181,1834]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Pyrgodesmus obscurus Pocock, 1892, male syntypes. 1. Original labels. 2. Both syntypes pierced with glass minutiae, shown relative to the length of an insect pin. 3. Habitus of a syntype, lateral view (after Pocock (1892)). 4. Picture of the same, lateral view. 5. Body rings 5–7 and gonopods in situ, ventral view. 6. Body rings 6–9 and gonopods in situ, ventrolateral view. 7 &amp; 8. Enlarged gonopods in situ, ventral and ventrolateral views, respectively. Figs 1–3, 7 and 8 not to scale. Images courtesy Dmitry Telnov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5709646" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5709646/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">Figs 5 &amp; 6</figureCitation>
). Gonopods (
<figureCitation id="40AA2A0ECE28550591832E44FD85FD8A" box="[437,560,583,609]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1857,1881]" captionTargetBox="[186,1401,181,1831]" captionTargetId="figure-15@2.[186,1401,181,1834]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Pyrgodesmus obscurus Pocock, 1892, male syntypes. 1. Original labels. 2. Both syntypes pierced with glass minutiae, shown relative to the length of an insect pin. 3. Habitus of a syntype, lateral view (after Pocock (1892)). 4. Picture of the same, lateral view. 5. Body rings 5–7 and gonopods in situ, ventral view. 6. Body rings 6–9 and gonopods in situ, ventrolateral view. 7 &amp; 8. Enlarged gonopods in situ, ventral and ventrolateral views, respectively. Figs 1–3, 7 and 8 not to scale. Images courtesy Dmitry Telnov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5709646" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5709646/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">Figs 7 &amp; 8</figureCitation>
) relatively simple, 
<emphasis id="EAE5EA99CE285505933B2E44FCE7FD8B" box="[781,850,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">in situ</emphasis>
held almost parallel to each other, with only tips of telopodites (= solenomeres), both slightly curved ventrad and poorly bifid, crossing medially; each gonopod consisting of a large, globose, densely microsetose and micropapillate coxite and a unipartite, rather long, ribbon-shaped, distally attenuating telopodite/solenomere curved caudad, strongly sunken inside a deep gonocoel and terminating the seminal groove on top.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
